By: Daniel Feliciano, MS (Public Health),

Argentina’s government has been at the center of a global firestorm after it unveiled new legislation that would allow for abortion in the first 14 weeks of gestation by a simple majority vote in congress. Had the vote stuck to a simple majority, it would have been passed to the country’s upper house, where restrictions on women’s access to abortion would likely lead to its passage. One step closer to overturning the ban would be to move the vote over to a referendum, collecting enough signatures to make women’s access to safe and legal abortion a constitutional right.
